newsitem.title: USA: U.S. West Coast crudes keep rising late with WTI.
newsitem.headline: U.S. West Coast crudes keep rising late with WTI.

text.p: U.S. West Coast crude prices continued rising late Friday, amid Oct/Nov spread trade for West Texas Intermediate/Cushing crude.

Local talk deadened late, as traders left the market early for the weekend and large producers evaluating their November sales programs. Alaska North Slope (ANS) bids stayed $2.50 off November with a big seller at $2.00 off October WTI.
Outright prices for ANS were $22.15/22.45 a barrel, up 25 cents from early. Differentials remained at 2.30 off November, the level of the deal done earlier this week.
Line 63 remained unchanged at $3.20 to $3.00 under spot WTI for November delivery.
California heavy crude Kern River were unchanged at $16.15/16.35 a barrel.
And prices for lightly traded Wilmington crude oil held at $17.60/17.70.
